{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a1e55339-8eb7-42b4-9500-e4b82b7fba91","content":"\n\nIn ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request**. MAUI has no equivalent request boundary, so a scoped service effectively behaves like a **singleton** — the same `DbContext` instance lives for the entire app lifetime. Its change tracker accumulates stale entities across navigations.\n\n**Fixes (pick one):**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — a fresh `DbContext` per injection point:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddTransient<AppDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n2. **Use `IDbContextFactory`** and control the lifetime yourself:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<AppDbContext>();\n   ```\n   Then in your view model:\n   ```csharp\n   using var db = _factory.CreateDbContext();\n   ```\n\nOption 2 is generally preferred — it makes the short lifetime explicit and avoids accidental sharing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cb1c936e-9972-4994-8948-b94a4ee45185","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common gotcha when moving from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scopes and DbContext lifetime. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to explore any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request. In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request, so `AddScoped` behaves essentially like `AddSingleton` — the same instance lives for the entire app lifetime. That's why the DbContext's change tracker retains stale/cached data across page navigations.","outputTokens":378},"id":"294e8530-263a-46e4-841c-297f73a5216b","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:43:06.534Z","parentId":"9fe98400-5788-499d-bba5-9ba5ace7fca1"}
